From: martin@chemeng.ed.ac.uk (Martin Spenceley)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 24 Aug 1993 11:35:50 +0100


In article <Aug23.132337.20908@acs.ucalgary.ca>, bstone@acs.ucalgary.ca (Blake Stone) writes:
>> > of course, I've never seen a polished GUI UNIX app. *Ever*.
>> > (Unless you call NeXTStep UNIX).
>
>> But there are gazillions of non-GUI Un*x apps. Not all the
>> world needs mice and windows.
>
>However the mainstream market has certainly indicated that mice
>'n windows is definitely where it wants to be.  The technical and
>scientific communities are a separate issue, although even those
>would prefer a graphical interface all other things being equal
>(which they most certainly are not).
>

Why did it take almost 6 years after the Mac was lauched before GUI's
become popular on PC's? Why is WINDOWS still not as good as the Mac
GUI and why after 6 years to get it right has Microsoft not done so? Also
why does Microsoft provide one of the worst API's to develop it in?

The technical and Scientific communities also require GUIs. It is just
that the market is much smaller and money to develop them is hard to
come by. But that's a separate issue.....

>> And nothing prevents software developers from writing decent
>> GUIs for Un*x, of course.
>
>Then why don't they?
>
>Nothing prevents you from walking on the moon either.  Something,
>does indeed discourage either from occuring:  Lack of support.
>Neither X nor Motif nor OpenLook provide a complete enough set of
>tools to make writing polished apps a profitable exercise.

I've never heard so much BOL***KS in all my life! 

What tools are you talking about? GUI Builders? There's plenty of them
(I've used UIMX and DevGuide both excellent builders). OPEN LOOK also has 
one  of the easiest API's (XView) there is for any GUI system.

I have used many GUI toolkits over the years including Motif, DEC-Windows, 
Xlib, XIntrinsics, MS-Windows, Amiga Intuition/Gadtools, XView and Mac 
Finder. I believe I can write an OPEN LOOK application as much as 20% faster than I could using either the Motif or MS-WINDOWS APIs.

Currently I'm developing OPEN LOOK applications for process engineering
applications simply because I could develop them faster using XView than I 
could using almost any other API (except probably Nextstep). Doing the things
I want to do could not be accomplished using MS-WINDOWS API.

The OPEN LOOK toolkit is a very well thought out GUI style and has as
much, if not more functionality than Windows.

The main reason why there are more Windows based applications is that
the market see a greater profitability serving the lemmings mentality
of the Windows market. 'No gain without pain' as one Windows programmer 
friend succinctly put it.

>True, polished GUI apps exist under Windows, Windows NT, OS/2,
>the Mac OS and NeXTSTEP.
>

There are polished GUI applications under Motif and OPEN LOOK. You've
just not looked any further than the length of your 'Windows based Word
Processor'.  Take a look at FrameMaker for OPEN LOOK and Motif for
instance.  Also I think Sun's OPEN WINDOWS desktop environment is also
very well designed and is a far better user front end than the
MS-Windows system.  (I wish when Sun move over to the COSE (Motif)
system that they put the OPEN LOOK tools to the public domain.) :-)

Even some public domain applications, like Ftptool and XVnews, are very well designed.  (Is it any co-incidence these are written using XView?) 

Although I do not use Linux or Windows/NT, I find it difficult to see
how you can compare like with like. NT is _supposed_ to be a
'professional' commerically developed operating system while Linux (I
believe) has not had any such pretentions. I suppose it is embarrasing
to Microsoft and their lemmings (sorry, I mean users :-) that a public
domain operating system can be compared so favourably to New Technology
(NOT). When will people realise Microsoft is taking them for a ride,
after 7 versions (and 10 years) of MS-DOS it's still not much better
than CP/M!  With Microsoft being able to take every PC user to the
cleaners for every small improvement to MS-DOS do you think it will not
be any different with Windows or NT upgrades? Take NT, it really has
not been a real big improvement from a _user_ point of view, it still
looks like WINDOWS. To the average user NT only multi-tasks better than
WINDOWS 3.1 (when the user has added the extra 12 Meg that is :-)

I wish Linux every success. Maybe one day I'll port my OPEN LOOK
applications to Linux. The only problem with that is I'd have to
sacific my other bug-bear and buy a PC ;-)

Martin.














