Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: tjrc1@mbfs.bio.cam.ac.uk (Tim Cutts (Zoology))
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Tue, 24 Aug 1993 13:49:39 GMT

martin@chemeng.ed.ac.uk (Martin Spenceley) writes:


>In article <Aug23.132337.20908@acs.ucalgary.ca>, bstone@acs.ucalgary.ca (Blake Stone) writes:

>Why did it take almost 6 years after the Mac was lauched before GUI's
>become popular on PC's? Why is WINDOWS still not as good as the Mac
>GUI and why after 6 years to get it right has Microsoft not done so? Also
>why does Microsoft provide one of the worst API's to develop it in?

MS Windows interface is not necessarily worse.  I personally prefer it to the
Mac.  For instance I *hate* the way you only have one menu bar on screen,
which means that an application can all but disappear, and then a non-expert
user whinges to me that nothing will run due to insufficient memory...

However, I love the trashcan idea.  There are things in X (like the mouse
cut/paste and the scrollbars), that are infinitely superior to either MSWin or
the Mac.  It's all a matter of personal taste.

>What tools are you talking about? GUI Builders? There's plenty of them
>(I've used UIMX and DevGuide both excellent builders). OPEN LOOK also has 
>one  of the easiest API's (XView) there is for any GUI system.

Yes, but do you have anything as nice as a Borland IDE?  I agree, XView is free
as are a few other toolkits, but tools of the standard of ease of use of
Borland's compilers tend to be *$%# expensive under Unix.  This is fine for
academic institutions and corporations, but for PC users looking for an OS it
is a major hurdle.  This is one reason I use both MS Windoze and Linux/X on my
PC.

>I have used many GUI toolkits over the years including Motif, DEC-Windows, 
>Xlib, XIntrinsics, MS-Windows, Amiga Intuition/Gadtools, XView and Mac 
>Finder. I believe I can write an OPEN LOOK application as much as 20% faster
>than I could using either the Motif or MS-WINDOWS APIs.

I must admit that so far the MS Windows API is the only one I have tried.  This
is because I use Pascal, and not C, and so far there is no such thing as a
Pascal compiler that will generate X code in any shape or form that I can
find.

One day I'll have to learn C, but time is not available at present.

>I wish Linux every success. Maybe one day I'll port my OPEN LOOK
>applications to Linux. The only problem with that is I'd have to
>sacific my other bug-bear and buy a PC ;-)

Porting them shouldn't be a problem.  If you wrote them nicely, just a
recompilation with the Linux XView libraries and you'd be away...

Tim.
