Date: Tue, 24 Aug 1993 10:59:29 EDT
From: <BJT105@psuvm.psu.edu>
Subject: Re: Why not create/use auto VESA SVGA X11 drivers? (Possible FAQ entry

The reason it hasn't (won't?) be done is all that VESA code is sitting in
16-bit real-mode BIOS code on the board, and a 32-bit operating system can't
get at it directly.  As far as I know, the only way to write a "VESA" driver
for a 32-bit OS would be to start a virtual 8086 process which has exclusive
rights to the screen and services all graphics operations.  Between the slow
VESA calls and the context switch to the graphics process (!), I think this
would be too slow to be usable.

Bernie

------------------------------

From: jstump@austin.ibm.com (John E. Stump)
Subject: Re: How are the Linux Packages put Together?
Date: Tue, 24 Aug 1993 15:36:15 GMT

In article <CC516H.7y7@boulder.parcplace.com> imp@boulder.parcplace.com (Warner Losh) writes:
>tar cfz foo.tgz a b c d e f g ...
>
>where a b c d e f g ... are the files that are in package foo.  The
>shell script known as sysinstall is 328 lines.  It would be easy to
>write one that just extracted packages from a disk.  However, it would
>be harder to come up with a complete install package that you could
>install from scratch with.
>
>I would imagine that someone could come up with an SLS replacement.  I
>think that the first version would take about a day to hack together.
>However, it would likely take several months before it is as stable
>and robust as the SLS scripts are.  I'm sure that the slackware folks
>could easily come up with something that isn't the SLS scripts, but
>works well enough to begin distributions again.

I envision an "official" linux installation system that no one really
owns, but it's something everyone can use and documentation can be
based on that. There would be no need for all these competing
distributions.

The idea is to have a simple install program that is able to install
independent software packages. One such package (mandatory) would be
the kernel and boot package, another mandatory package would be the base
operating system utilities. Pretty much all other software packages
would be optional, such as the development tools, X, TeX, etc.

The software packages would be similar to the series disks in the SLS
distribution, but a little more organized and with some ryhme and reason
to whats on them.

These packages would be put together and stored somewhere at one of the
sites and the user can build his own installation distribution by
collecting the packages he/she wants. Perhaps a description file can be
manually or automatically generated to describe what is in the
distribution. Run the install program, select what you want, hit GO, and
let it churn away.

The maintainer of each of the packages can easily build the
installation packages, that way, no one person is responsible for
maintaining an entire distribution.

Just a few thoughts.

>-- 
>Warner Losh            imp@boulder.parcplace.COM       ParcPlace Boulder
>I've almost finished my brute force solution to subtlety.

john
